{
  "text": "Thermal conductivity (k) of the test specimens is measured using a cut-bar test facility under steady state conditions. The system is assumed to have attained steady state conditions when all the temperature sensors (thermocouples) indicate a constant value with a variation of less than \u00b10.5 0 C. Variation of thermal conductivity as a function of mean bulk temperature is determined. Complete details of experimental procedure are described elsewhere [CITATION_1] . When compared to pure PDMS, there is a remarkable enhancement (an order of magnitude) in thermal conductivity of PDMS loaded with carbon black nano-particles in varying proportions. For example specimens with 10 wt % carbon black, the PDMS acquired thermal conductivity of 2.07 Wm -1 K -1 as against 0.17 Wm -1 K -1 for PDMS without carbon black (see ref. [CITATION_2] ). The experimental results also showed that the thermal conductivity of the samples increased in general with the percentage (10-25%) of carbon black present in the composite. This is attributed to the increase in conductive pathway and network density with increased number of filler particles [8] . The thermal conductivity data of the present experimental investigation is more promising when compared to the investigations carried out earlier by other researchers. For example, the thermal conductivity of epoxy resin with 70wt% carbon black nano filler is 1.8 Wm -1 K -1 [9] . Where as in our present experimental investigation, we found that a thermal conductivity value of 2.07 Wm -1 K -1 can be achieved with a 10 wt % of carbon black in PDMS. This means, one needs a less wt% (almost seven times) carbon black in the case of PDMS as compared to epoxy resin to achieve same or a little higher values of thermal conductivity. Carbon black as a nano filler in PDMS is more effective in improving thermal conductivity than in epoxy resin.",
  "citation_candidates": [
